# --- RSVP rollout (once) ---
# 1) Paste scripts/rsvp-webapp.gs into the Sheet’s Apps Script project.
# 2) Run: npm run rsvp:secret → copy hex → Apps Script → Project Settings → Script properties →
#    RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET (optional but recommended).
# 3) Deploy → Web app: Execute as Me, Who has access: Anyone (anonymous). New version after edits.
# 4) Share nothing extra — script is bound to your spreadsheet already.
# 5) `.env` is gitignored; copy this file to `.env`, fill URLs/secrets locally only.
#    Local `npm run dev` proxies POSTs to script.google.com (see vite.config.ts) so CORS does not block.
#    Production (GitHub Pages) posts as application/x-www-form-urlencoded payload=… for reliable Apps Script handling.
# 6) GitHub repo → Settings → Secrets → Actions: VITE_RSVP_SCRIPT_URL and (optional) VITE_RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET.
#
# Copy to `.env` for local dev (or `.env.local` if you use that).
# Google Apps Script Web App URL (deployed as "Anyone" and writes to your sheet).
# Script source lives in-repo: scripts/rsvp-webapp.gs (paste into Apps Script editor).
# If opening the /exec URL in an incognito tab shows Google Sign-in, redeploy the Web app
# with "Who has access: Anyone" (anonymous), not restricted to Google accounts.
# For GitHub Pages CI: add the same value as repo secret VITE_RSVP_SCRIPT_URL
# (Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions).
VITE_RSVP_SCRIPT_URL=

# Optional: shared with Apps Script → Project Settings → Script properties → RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET
# (Adds the same string to GitHub Actions secrets as VITE_RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET if you use it.)
VITE_RSVP_WEBHOOK_SECRET=

# Legacy Supabase variables (optional; keep only if other parts of the app still use Supabase).
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=
VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=
